Graphical abstract The use of electrogenerated H2O2 in wastewater treatment is a promising method to degrade the potentially hazardous organic contaminants. Hydrothermally prepared nanocomposites of Nb2O5 nanoparticles on reduced graphene oxide (rGO) were tested toward the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR), via the production of H2O2. The Nb2O5-rGO composite shifts the onset potential to less negatives values when compared to unmodified rGO and Printex 6L carbon. Moreover, an increase in H2O2 production in acidic media from 73.7% to 85.3% was observed for rGO and Nb2O5-rGO, respectively. Nonetheless, the activity of both catalysts in alkaline medium is not significantly different. When compared to carbon Printex, the standard for this type of reaction, the Nb2O5-rGO electrode gives higher yields of H2O2 in either acidic (70.5% vs. 85.3%) or alkaline media (63.4% vs. 74.9%). The selectivity of Nb2O5-rGO composite toward H2O2 formation is attributed to the synergistic effect between the Nb2O5 nanoparticles and the rGO sheets. Keywords Nanostructured reduced graphene oxide Niobium pentoxide Oxygen reduction reaction Hydrogen peroxide electrogeneration 1 Introduction Organic effluents can be treated by physical–chemical processes, biological digestion or thermal incineration, the latter being mostly used in solid waste management. The physical–chemical methods are based on physical separation of phases and, in spite of their wide application, the contaminants are not destroyed. Biological oxidative processes use aerobic and anaerobic digestion tanks and activated sludges. They are characterized by a lower oxygen demand and low cost, but require long treatment time before the effluents reach the appropriate quality standards. In contrast, electrochemical methods may effectively respond to this problem by providing potent oxidant compounds such as the hydroxyl radical ( OH) which are capable of oxidizing a wide variety of organic compounds to CO2, H2O and inorganic salts. In this context, the electro-Fenton reaction [1–3] provides an excellent example of a cooperative system in which the in situ cathodic production of hydrogen peroxide is coupled with a degradative anodic processes [4]. Hydrogen peroxide, a chemical source of the hydroxyl radical, can be produced electrochemically by the reduction of oxygen. This process involves a two-electron pathway [5,6], as shown by Eqs. (I) and (II), in acid and alkaline media, respectively: (I) O 2 + 2 H + + 2 e - → H 2 O 2 (II) O 2 + H 2 O + 2 e - → HO 2 - + OH - The hydrogen peroxide that is formed can be further reduced as shown by Eqs. (III) and (IV): (III) H 2 O 2 + 2 H + + 2 e - → 2 H 2 O (IV) HO 2 - + 2 e - + H 2 O → 3 OH - However, the oxygen reduction on planar electrodes has limitations due to the concentration of the oxygen in the bulk of the solution and due to its diffusion to the electrode surface. This limitation can be controlled using three-dimensional electrodes known as Gas Diffusion Electrodes (GDEs) [1,2,7–10]. The GDEs have a highly porous structure, allowing the oxygen permeation through it to the electrolyte solution by pressure difference. The ORR occurs at this solid–liquid–gas interface, and allows the generation of H2O2 in situ [11,12]. Various electrocatalysts have been developed to enhance the ORR activity and current efficiency for H2O2 electrogeneration. For this purpose, many authors have studied cathodic materials including quinones [13–17], metal-phthalocyanines [18–20], carbon nanotubes [21,22], transition metal oxides [23–28] and others [29–34], directly mixed or supported on carbon. However, the development of electrode materials that enable the ORR mechanism through a two-electron pathway with high selectivity and at low overpotential is still of great importance. Graphene sheets were isolated by Geim group in 2004 [35] and much attention has been given to both fundamental properties and applications of this material [35–37]. It exhibits excellent physical and chemical properties, such as high electrical conductivity [38,39], high surface area [40,41], and a large number of electrochemically favorable edge carbons per mass of graphene. These characteristics facilitate the electron transfer between molecules and the substrate with a low overpotential [42,43]. It has been reported that graphene and graphene oxide can be used in electrochemical sensors [44,45], capacitors [46,47], lithium batteries [48,49], and solar cells [50], and as catalysts for fuel oxidation [41,51]. There are also many reports on its utilization for ORR, either as catalyst support material or as catalyst itself aiming fuel cell applications [32,37,52–60]. The hydrothermal method has been applied to the synthesis of many different graphene nanocomposites, namely CuO/graphene [61], NiO/graphene [62], ZnO/graphene [63] and FeS2/graphene [64]. At the same time, the H2O2 electrogeneration on non-noble metal oxides supported on nanostructured graphene, has not yet been fully explored [28]. Therefore, in this study we investigate on the properties of reduced graphene oxide sheets and Nb2O5 nanoparticles supported on reduced graphene oxide for the electrocatalysis of oxygen reduction in acid and alkaline media. Niobium oxide was chosen for its acidic features [65,66], that increase the acidity of the composite surface providing greater hydrophilicity and consequently higher activity toward the ORR [23,67]. The electrochemical performance of these materials was compared with Printex 6L carbon, which is used as a reference material for H2O2 electrogeneration [68]. Noteworthy, this is the first report on the catalysis of Nb2O5-rGO composite toward ORR. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials Natural graphite flakes (+100 mesh, ⩾75%), potassium permanganate (99%), sulfuric acid (98%), phosphoric acid (85%), hydrogen peroxide (30%), anhydrous ethanol and anhydrous ether with ACS grade or higher were obtained from Sigma–Aldrich (Canada). Niobium ammonium oxalate (NH4[NbO(C2O4)·H2O]) was acquired from Companhia Brasileira de Metalurgia e Mineração (CBMM – Brazil), Printex 6L carbon was purchased from Evonic (Brazil), and Nafion® solution (5wt%) was bought from Sigma–Aldrich (Brazil). All chemicals were used as received and solutions were prepared using deionized water (Millipore Milli-Q). Ultra-high purity nitrogen (N2) and oxygen (O2) gases (Linde) were used for the deaeration of solutions and the preparation of O2-saturated solutions, respectively. 2.2 Preparation of rGO and Nb2O5-rGO Graphene oxide (GO) was prepared by the modified Hummer’s method from graphite flakes (3g) and KMnO4 (18g) in the presence of a mixture of sulfuric acid–phosphoric acid (9:1). Briefly, graphite was mixed with sulfuric acid (360mL) and phosphoric acid 85% (40mL) [69]. Then KMnO4 was added at once. The color of the thick mixture turned green rapidly and an exothermic reaction was observed increasing the temperature of the mixture to 45°C. The mixture was heated to 50°C and stirred for 12h; then, the thick mixture was allowed to cool down to room temperature and poured slowly over a mixture of ice (400mL) and hydrogen peroxide 30% (6mL) for neutralization. The mixture was sifted using a metallic drum-sieve (297μm) to remove the solid particles from the suspension of graphene oxide. The resulting GO was washed in succession with nanopure water (200mL), HCl 30% (200mL) and ethanol 100% (2×200mL). The GO solution was dispersed in anhydrous ether (400mL). The material was suspended in nanopure water (5mg/mL–650mL) using magnetic stirring (12h) and sonication (1h). The chemical reduction of GO and the synthesis of Nb2O5 nanoparticles supported on reduced graphene oxide (rGO) were synthesized by the hydrothermal method following the procedure described by Liang et al. for Co3O4 on rGO [52]. In brief, the graphene oxide suspension was further diluted in anhydrous ethanol (EtOH) to a final concentration of ∼0.33mgmL−1. First, NH4[NbO(C2O4)·H2O] was solubilized in water and added to GO in EtOH suspension at room temperature. The mass proportion of Nb/GO used was 15% (w/w). The reaction was kept at 80°C under stirring for 10h. After that, the reaction mixture was transferred to a 100mL autoclave for hydrothermal reaction at 150°C for 3h. The product was collected by centrifugation, washed with water and lyophilized. The rGO sheets were synthesized following the same procedure of Nb2O5-rGO composite but without adding metallic precursor in the first step. Fig. 1 illustrates the route for the preparation of rGO and Nb2O5-rGO composite. 2.3 Chemical physical characterization X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis of the samples was carried out using a Bruker D-8 Advance X-ray diffractometer with a Cu Kα radiation source (λ =1.54056Å) operating at 40kV and 40mA. The morphology and microstructure of the composites were investigated by transmission electron microscopy (TEM). Transmission electron micrographs were obtained with a JEOL 2100F operated at 200kV. For Nb2O5, the TEM samples were prepared by dipping the copper grids into the powder samples already dispersed in methanol. For the rGO-based samples, lacey carbon TEM grids were used instead. The surface chemical composition was investigated by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). XPS spectra were obtained on a VG Escalab 220i-XL using a polychromatic Al source (Al Kα=1486.6eV) with a base pressure of 1×10−9 torr. The spectrum was acquired with a hemispherical analyzer (pass energy=20eV) and the detection was performed with six single-channel detectors. All measurements were performed using an X-ray power of 400W (15kV×26mA). The peak fittings were performed using the CasaXPS software. The background correction was performed using a Shirley background. The spectra were fitted with Peak shapes modeled using Gaussian Laurentzian profile. The C1s photoelectron peak at 284.6eV was used as an internal standard for the correction of all samples. 2.4 Electrochemical characterization Electrochemical measurements were performed using a potentiostat/galvanostat Autolab PGSTAT 128N (Metrohm) with a rotating ring-disk electrode (RRDE) system (Pine Instruments). The electrochemical studies were carried out in a home-built electrochemical cell using an Ag/AgCl electrode as the reference electrode and a Pt plate as the counter electrode. For electrode preparation, 1mg of catalyst was dispersed in 1mL of isopropanol for 30min under sonication. Then 20μL portion of the suspension was slowly dropped on the disk surface of the glassy carbon electrode (5.6mm in diameter). After drying, 20μL of the Nafion® aqueous solution (0.05%) was added to the surface of the microlayer. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) curves were recorded in N2 and O2 saturated 0.1molL−1 K2SO4 (pH=2) and 0.1molL−1 NaOH at a sweep rate of 50mVs−1. The linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) curves were conducted in N2(g) and O2(g) saturated electrolyte solution. All the LSVs curves presented in this work were corrected by subtracting of the background current recorded in N2-satured solution. RRDE measurements were carried out at a scan rate of 5mVs−1. The Pt ring electrode was kept at +1.0V in acid solution and +0.5V in alkaline media for oxidation of peroxide produced at the disk electrode. All the experiments were performed at room temperature. Printex 6L carbon (Evonik) was used as reference material for the oxygen reduction reaction involving two-electron process. The stability of Nb2O5-rGO catalyst was tested on fresh electrode by chronoamperometry at −0.3V for 5.5h in O2-satured solution 0.1molL−1 K2SO4 (pH=2) and 0.1molL−1 NaOH, at a sweep rate of 5mVs−1. Furthermore, linear sweep voltammograms were recorded before and after the chronoamperometry. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 XRD, TEM and XPS analysis X-ray diffractograms recorded for GO, rGO and Nb2O5-rGO composite are presented in Fig. 2 . Graphene oxide exhibits a characteristic diffraction peak at ca. 2θ =10° (Fig. 2A) [54,70–72]. This diffraction pattern changed after the hydrothermal reaction, and a broad reflection from 20° to 30° characteristic of the rGO sheets [54,57,71,72] was observed (Fig. 2B). This result, evidences the conversion of GO to rGO. The peaks at 22.6°, 28.4° and 36.6°, as shown in the XRD pattern of Nb2O5-rGO electrocatalyst (Fig. 2C), correspond to the (001), (180) and (181) planes of orthorhombic Nb2O5 phase according to JCPDS#30-873 database (Fig. 2D). In previous reports, the Nb2O5 amorphous phase is observed when niobium oxide is synthesized at 150°C i.e., the Nb2O5 crystalline phase is only observed at a temperature higher than 400°C [73,74]. In this work, crystalline Nb2O5 nanoparticles supported on rGO were successfully obtained at 150°C by the hydrothermal method. This temperature allows the presence of Bronsted and Lewis acid sites on the Nb2O5-rGO composite [74], which can promote ORR process. Transmission electron microscopy revealed that pure niobium oxide crystalline nanoparticles shape in the form of “fava beans” of 100×200nm (Fig. 3 A). A slight agglomeration of the nanoparticles is expected due to the lack of any surfactant agent (Fig. 3B). The high resolution TEM (HRTEM) image (Fig. 3C) shows that these structures are composed of 5×10nm nanocrystal-platelets visible at the edges. For the Printex 6L carbon, no reaction was detected except for a small amount of hydrogen that evolves at more negative potentials than −0.40V in N2-saturated solution. However, in O2-satured solution, there is one cathodic peak at ca. −0.47V which can be attributed to the 2-electron electrochemical reduction of O2 to H2O2 at the carbon surface. The voltammogram for the rGO electrode in N2-saturated electrolyte shows a blurred peak from +0.4V to 0.0V. The redox transition can be assigned to the presence of quinone groups on the composite surface in agreement with XPS data [16,34,84]. In O2-satured solution, one additional peak was obtained at −0.21V on rGO electrode related to O2 reduction. The reduction peak current (−0.2mA) is two times higher than that of obtained with Printex 6L electrode (−0.1mA). This higher reduction current for the rGO electrode is also associated with its larger effective surface area in comparison with the Printex 6L electrode. In fact, the capacitive current and the integrated voltammetric charge (q =221.9mC), which are proportional to the electrochemical surface area of the electrode materials [85,86], of the rGO electrode in N2-satured solution is much higher than those of the Printex 6L electrode (q =32.5mC). Furthermore, the ORR peak potential of the rGO electrode is more positive than the one for Printex 6L, suggesting that the rGO electrode exhibits higher electrocatalytic activity toward the reduction of O2 in acid solution than Printex 6L. The cyclic voltammogram of Nb2O5-rGO electrode in N2-saturated solution is similar to that of rGO and the integrated voltammetric charge is 282.7mC. The increase in the area of the cathodic peak (at ca. +0.15V) can be associated with the existence of the redox transition from Nb(V) to Nb(IV), i.e. Nb2O5/NbO2 in agreement with potential-pH equilibrium diagram for the niobium–water system, at 25°C, described by Pourbaix [87]. In O2-satured solution, the cathodic peak related to ORR appears at ca. −0.25V. Oxygen reduction reaction measurements, were performed using rotating ring-disk electrode (RRDE) to monitor the formation of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) during the ORR process [88]. This indicates high H2O2 electrogeneration for rGO and Nb2O5-rGO. Moreover, the half-wave potential for ORR on Nb2O5-rGO catalysts is ca. 37mV and on rGO is ca. 86mV lower than that of Printex 6L, which enables 2-electron ORR at lower overpotential. Thus, the production rate of H2O2 is higher than 85% at potentials from −0.2 to −0.4V and drops to ca. 67% at potentials more negative than −0.5V. In contrast, no significant variations of nt and I(H2O2)% values were observed for rGO and Printex 6L supports. The ORR electrocatalytic properties were also examined in 0.1molL−1 NaOH solution within the potential range from +0.2 to −1.2V vs. Ag/AgCl. Finally, the stability of Nb2O5-rGO catalyst was tested on fresh electrodes by chronoamperometry at −0.3V for 5.5h in O2-satured solution 0.1molL−1 K2SO4 (pH=2) and 0.1molL−1 NaOH. As shown in Fig. 13 A, the current was quite stable in both cases. Moreover, the linear sweep voltammograms recorded before and after the chronoamperometry, Fig. 13B and C, overlap again demonstrating the stable performance of the catalyst. Our results show that the ORR activity to H2O2 electrogeneration on the rGO catalyst, in both acid and alkaline media, occurs at lower overpotential and with higher selectivity with respect to Printex 6L catalyst. Recently, it has been reported that the oxygen-containing functional groups of carbon surface can improve the ORR activity [77–81,91]. In this context, the ketone groups (CO) act as active sites for ORR due the delocalization of the π-electron increasing the kinetics of reaction [92]. Therefore, the better electrocatalytic activity of the rGO sheets can be related to the fraction of oxygenated groups presented on the surface of graphene: 47.6% of rGO versus 33.6% of the Printex 6L according to XPS data. Furthermore, the high catalytic activity observed for the Nb2O5-rGO electrocatalyst can be also associated with the transfer of electrons from Nb(V) to O2 related to redox transition in the region of oxygen reduction. The ORR mechanism depends on the way that oxygen molecules couple with the electrode surface according to Griffith, Pauling and Bridge models [6,93]. The Griffiths and Bridge models favor the formation of water by the four-electron pathway while the Pauling model favors H2O2 formation by two-electron transfer. The different forms of O2 adsorption on the material surface may occur simultaneously, however several factors may influence the contribution of each interaction such as the distance between the adsorption sites, the type of active site and the amount of oxygen present. Probably oxygen adsorbs on Nb2O5-rGO preferentially by the Pauling model in which the oxygen molecule interacts in an end-on position with no rupture of the OO bond generating H2O2 as product [6,93,94]. Consequently, the well-distributed Nb2O5 nanoparticles on rGO sheets act as additional electroactive sites resulting in a more favorable electron-transfer kinetic for ORR through two-electron pathway. Most of the reports on graphene or graphene-supported nanoparticles for ORR aim the H2O production, i.e. fuel cell applications. However, Barros et al. [28] studied Fe3O4 nanoparticles supported on graphene for ORR to H2O2 electrogeneration in 1.0molL−1 KOH using RRDE system at 1600rpm. The authors found the yield of H2O2 production equal to 62.0%. In this work, we have obtained 74.9% of H2O2 production in 0.1molL−1 NaOH and 85.3% in 0.1molL−1 K2SO4 (pH=2) at 900rpm. Therefore, this composite is a promising material to be used as cathode material in gas diffusion electrode for H2O2 production. 4 Conclusions In summary, Nb2O5 nanoparticles on reduced graphene oxide sheets were prepared by hydrothermal reaction, where the reduction of GO and the in situ generation of Nb2O5 nanoparticles occurred simultaneously. The Nb2O5-rGO composite displays higher electrochemical activity for the ORR than rGO and Printex 6L carbon, showing the highest ring current corresponding to a higher amount of H2O2 produced. The yield of H2O2 electrogeneration on Nb2O5-rGO electrode is 85.3% in acid solution and 74.9% in alkaline solution whereas for rGOs sheets the H2O2 electrogeneration is 73.7% and 72.9%, respectively. Finally, for Printex 6L carbon the yields were 70.5% and 63.4%. In addition, the Nb2O5-rGO nanocomposite shifts the peak potential in the positive direction, enabling two-electron ORR at low overpotential, and shows very good durability in both media. Thus, the high performance of Nb2O5-rGO electrocatalyst makes it viable alternative to Gas Diffusion Electrodes for hydrogen peroxide in situ production for organic wastewater treatment applications. coredata.dc:description: The use of electrogenerated H2O2 in wastewater treatment is a promising method to degrade the potentially hazardous organic contaminants. Hydrothermally prepared nanocomposites of Nb2O5 nanoparticles on reduced graphene oxide (rGO) were tested toward the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR), via the production of H2O2. The Nb2O5-rGO composite shifts the onset potential to less negatives values when compared to unmodified rGO and Printex 6L carbon. Moreover, an increase in H2O2 production in acidic media from 73.7% to 85.3% was observed for rGO and Nb2O5-rGO, respectively. Nonetheless, the activity of both catalysts in alkaline medium is not significantly different. When compared to carbon Printex, the standard for this type of reaction, the Nb2O5-rGO electrode gives higher yields of H2O2 in either acidic (70.5% vs. 85.3%) or alkaline media (63.4% vs. 74.9%). The selectivity of Nb2O5-rGO composite toward H2O2 formation is attributed to the synergistic effect between the Nb2O5 nanoparticles and the rGO sheets.
coredata.dc:title: Nb2O5 nanoparticles supported on reduced graphene oxide sheets as electrocatalyst for the H2O2 electrogeneration
